The paper deals with polynomial bounds and their applications in query complexity and analysis of Boolean functions, which are topics commonly studied in theoretical computer science. The use of multilinear polynomials and decoupling techniques suggests a focus on computational complexity (cs.CC) and information theory (cs.IT). The mention of tail-bound comparisons and consequences for analysis of Boolean functions suggests a focus on probability and statistics (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the mention of optimal sharpening of the DFKO Inequality suggests a focus on computational geometry (cs.CG).
